            <fr:title text="Sheafification › "><fr:link href="algm-001J.xml" title="Sheafification" addr="algm-001J" type="local">Sheafification</fr:link> › </fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>We construct sheafification as <fr:link href="algm-001G.xml" title="Iterated plus construction produces a sheaf" addr="algm-001G" type="local">an iterated plus construction</fr:link>. This produces a functor. By <fr:link href="algm-001H.xml" title="Universal property of plus construction" addr="algm-001H" type="local">Theorem <fr:contextual-number addr="algm-001H" /></fr:link> we have a natural bijection
    <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\hom (P^{++}, F) \cong  \hom (P^+, F) \cong  \hom (P, F).]]></fr:tex>
    Hence it is indeed the left adjoint. Since the bijections are given by composition with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  P^+]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P^+ \to  P^{++}]]></fr:tex>, we see that the unit of the adjunction is given by the composition <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  P^{++}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>Alternatively, using <fr:link href="algm-001K.xml" title="Separation of presheaf" addr="algm-001K" type="local">Construction <fr:contextual-number addr="algm-001K" /></fr:link>, we may compose two adjunctions to first <fr:link href="algm-001K.xml" title="Separation of presheaf" addr="algm-001K" type="local">separate</fr:link> the presheaf, and then perform the plus construction. By uniqueness of adjunction these two constructions are equivalent.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
